Conveniently located right off St. Mary's Stop (Station) on the  "C" Greenline, this place makes some of the best Thai dishes I have had in Boston.  A nice cozy place with about 20 seat, and their specials on the wall, its a nice place to stop by and grab a bite or take away.  When you come, place the order at the register with the staff and if you eat in, they will bring it over to wherever you sit.  The Pad Thai noodles are nice and chewy and is served with a health portion of Shrimp.  The flavor is spot on and not greasy like some other places that I have been to.  The Indonesian fried rice was good by itself, however, the friend boneless chicken to me was a little too much on the fried side and could have been taken out to the fryer sooner.  However, that is just my opinion, as other people in my party thought it was perfect and matched with fried rice perfectly.  We also got the drunken noodles and that was AMAZING!!!! the flavor was so good and even though I was full, I could not stop eating it.  The noodles were cooked to perfection with a nice bounce to the noodle and the meat and veggies had a nice seer to.  I definitely a dish I will be ordering again.  For the portion and price, it can't be beat.  A great place to if you are in the mood for Thai.  FYI  - If you are eating there, be sure to clean up after yourself, there is a trash can and a cleaning station for you to put your dirty plates and utensils when you are done eating. (Can't tell you how many people I saw eat, and then leave without cleaning, even though there is a sign asking to please put dirty dishes in the bin.)

The option to add crispy chicken to any dish is pretty great, especially when paired with something like the green papaya salad. That said, this place has fairly typical Americanized Thai food—less flavorful, spicy, or fresh than one might hope for, but at this price point it’s not bad.  All in all, good value for a quick bite. The service is friendly and prompt and in my opinion, Giggling Rice is a good budget option on a block populated with generally pricier options. Also, in nicer weather this place expands their seating to the sidewalk.  Personally, other than the papaya salad, I’d say that the green curry is a good way to go.
